  "text": ". . ..you see silent refusal usually happened because someone sees like you have become a member of that family. . .so he/she feels if they tell you openly from now or from today I withdraw there may be a problem. . .because the family will not qualify to continue to be in the study, (FW1_male_FGD6) Finally, as FWs live and are embedded within communities beyond the study period, they were understandably careful that transient research activities should not spoil already established long-term relationships [CITATION_1] . With regards to the science of the study, by retaining silent refusals FWs feared they might collect low quality data, requiring repeated explanation to PIs. Whichever course of action FWs took, there were likely to be strained relationships, even if temporarily, between the FWs, participants and researchers.",
